Init Spark Session¶

In [ ]:
from pyspark.sql import SparkSession
import findspark


# if there is an existing Spark session, stop it to avoid conflicts
def stop_existing_spark():
    try:
        existing_spark = SparkSession.getActiveSession()
        if existing_spark:
            print("Stopping existing Spark session...")
            existing_spark.stop()
            print("Existing Spark session stopped.")
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error while stopping existing Spark session: {e}")


stop_existing_spark()


# Below line should be on top.
# to be able to find spark/pyspark installation and set up the SPARK_HOME environment variable
findspark.init()


print("Creating new Spark session...")

# Serialization converts objects into a format that can be stored or transmitted
# In Spark, when data moves between different processes or nodes, objects must be serialized
# 
# In our anime recommendation context:
# - User ratings, anime features, and model parameters need to be serialized when:
#   1. Shuffling data across partitions during joins (users + animes + ratings)
#   3. Saving/loading trained recommendation models to/from disk
#   4. Caching DataFrames in memory across cluster nodes
#
# Kryo serializer makes these operations faster and uses less memory compared to Java's default serializer
# This is especially important for recommendation systems that process large datasets with millions of ratings
# So, we configure Spark to use Kryo serialization for better performance and efficiency

spark = (
    SparkSession.builder.appName("AnimeRecommender")  # Application name for identification in Spark UI
    .master("local[*]")  # Run locally using all available CPU cores
    .config("spark.driver.memory", "6g")  # Allocate 6GB RAM to the driver process
    .config("spark.sql.shuffle.partitions", "100")  # Set number of partitions for shuffle operations (default is 200)
    .config("spark.network.timeout", "800s")  # Network timeout to prevent connection failures during long operations
    .config("spark.executor.heartbeatInterval", "30s")  # Frequency of heartbeat signals from executors to driver
    .config("spark.driver.extraJavaOptions", "-Xss12m")  # Increase driver JVM stack size to 12MB (prevents stack overflow)
    .config("spark.executor.extraJavaOptions", "-Xss12m")  # Increase executor JVM stack size to 12MB
    .config("spark.serializer", "org.apache.spark.serializer.KryoSerializer")  # Use faster Kryo serialization instead of Java serialization
    .config("spark.kryoserializer.buffer.max", "1024m")  # Maximum buffer size for Kryo serializer (1GB)
    .config("spark.kryo.unsafe", "true")  # Enable unsafe operations in Kryo for better performance
    .config("spark.kryo.referenceTracking", "false")  # Disable reference tracking in Kryo to improve performance
    .config("spark.rdd.compress", "true")  # Compress RDD data to save memory at cost of CPU
    .config("spark.memory.fraction", "0.7")  # Use 70% of heap space for execution and storage (30% for other operations)
    .config("spark.cleaner.referenceTracking.cleanCheckpoints", "true")  # Automatically clean up checkpoint files
    .config("spark.cleaner.periodicGC.interval", "30s")  # Run garbage collection every 30 seconds to free up memory
    .getOrCreate()
)


spark.sparkContext.setCheckpointDir("/tmp/spark-checkpoints")

# log only errors to reduce verbosity
spark.sparkContext.setLogLevel("ERROR")

print("New Spark session created:", spark.version)

Cleaning Dataset¶

We made some initial clean up in myanimelist dataset by removing the rows that has null values. Lets continue to further clean up process.

Lets work with animes which have more than 1 episodes.

In [309]:

We have almost 2000 animes less than 1 episodes. Some of them might be movies which have only 1 episodes. But for simplicity, lets continue with that.

Lets see the distribution of animes based on their member counts.

Using RDD and map to see members distribution¶

In [310]:
# Get members as RDD
member_counts_rdd = cleaned_animes_df.select("members").rdd.map(lambda row: int(row.members))

min_members = member_counts_rdd.min()
max_members = member_counts_rdd.max()
print(f"Minimum members: {min_members}")
print(f"Maximum members: {max_members}")

num_buckets = 10
bucket_size = (max_members - min_members) / num_buckets
print(f"Bucket size: {bucket_size}")

Minimum members: 37

In [311]:
def get_bucket_index(members, min_val, bucket_size, num_buckets):
    if members == min_val:
        return 0
    index = int((members - min_val) // bucket_size)
    # Ensure the last bucket includes the maximum value
    return min(index, num_buckets - 1)

bucketed_rdd = member_counts_rdd.map(lambda members: (get_bucket_index(members, min_members, bucket_size, num_buckets), 1))

bucket_counts_rdd = bucketed_rdd.reduceByKey(lambda a, b: a + b)
bucket_counts = bucket_counts_rdd.sortByKey().collect()

print("Bucket Counts:")
for bucket_index, count in bucket_counts:
    print(f"Bucket {bucket_index}: {count} animes")

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

bucket_indices = [item[0] for item in bucket_counts]
counts = [item[1] for item in bucket_counts]

bucket_ranges = []
for i in range(num_buckets):
    start = int(min_members + i * bucket_size)
    end = int(min_members + (i + 1) * bucket_size) - 1
    if i == num_buckets - 1:
        end = max_members
    bucket_ranges.append(f"{start}-{end}")

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.bar(bucket_indices, counts, tick_label=bucket_ranges)
plt.xlabel("Member Count Buckets")
plt.ylabel("Number of Animes")
plt.title("Distribution of Anime Member Counts")
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right")

Seems like a few hundered animes has more than 100k members. And just a few of them have over million members. Lets focus the ones less than 145670. Maybe we have just with a few members. Using map reduceByKey functions to see distribution of animes less than 145670 members¶

In [313]:
filtered_member_counts_rdd = member_counts_rdd.filter(lambda members: 37 <= members <= 145670)

min_filtered_members = filtered_member_counts_rdd.min()
max_filtered_members = filtered_member_counts_rdd.max()
num_filtered_buckets = 20
filtered_bucket_size = (max_filtered_members - min_filtered_members) / num_filtered_buckets

print(f"Minimum members (filtered): {min_filtered_members}")
print(f"Maximum members (filtered): {max_filtered_members}")
print(f"Filtered bucket size: {filtered_bucket_size}")


def get_filtered_bucket_index(members, min_val, bucket_size, num_buckets):
    if members == min_val:
        return 0
    index = int((members - min_val) // bucket_size)
    return min(index, num_buckets - 1)


filtered_bucketed_rdd = filtered_member_counts_rdd.map(
    lambda members: (
        get_filtered_bucket_index(members, min_filtered_members, filtered_bucket_size, num_filtered_buckets),
        1,
    )
)

filtered_bucket_counts_rdd = filtered_bucketed_rdd.reduceByKey(lambda a, b: a + b)
filtered_bucket_counts = filtered_bucket_counts_rdd.sortByKey().collect()

print("\nFiltered Bucket Counts:")
for bucket_index, count in filtered_bucket_counts:
    print(f"Bucket {bucket_index}: {count} animes")


filtered_bucket_indices = [item[0] for item in filtered_bucket_counts]
filtered_counts = [item[1] for item in filtered_bucket_counts]

filtered_bucket_ranges = []
for i in range(num_filtered_buckets):
    start = int(min_filtered_members + i * filtered_bucket_size)
    end = int(min_filtered_members + (i + 1) * filtered_bucket_size) - 1
    if i == num_filtered_buckets - 1:
        end = max_filtered_members
    filtered_bucket_ranges.append(f"{start}-{end}")

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 7))
plt.bar(filtered_bucket_indices, filtered_counts, tick_label=filtered_bucket_ranges)
plt.xlabel("Member Count Buckets (37 - 145670)")
plt.ylabel("Number of Animes")
plt.title("Distribution of Anime Member Counts (37 - 145670)")
plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha="right", fontsize=8)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Distrubtion of animes by count of voters¶

In [321]:
from pyspark.sql import functions as F
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

min_score = cleaned_animes_df.select(F.min("scored_by")).first()[0]
max_score = cleaned_animes_df.select(F.max("scored_by")).first()[0]
num_buckets = 10
bucket_size = (max_score - min_score) / num_buckets

bucketed_scored_by_df = cleaned_animes_df.withColumn(
    "bucket", F.floor((F.col("scored_by") - min_score) / bucket_size).cast("int")
)

# Count the number of animes in each bucket and collect all buckets
bucket_counts_scored_by_df = (
    bucketed_scored_by_df.groupBy("bucket")
    .agg(
        F.count("*").alias("count"),
        F.min("scored_by").alias("min_scored_by"),
        F.max("scored_by").alias("max_scored_by"),
    )
    .orderBy("bucket")
)

bucket_counts_scored_by = bucket_counts_scored_by_df.collect()

print("\nScored_by Bucket Counts:")
for row in bucket_counts_scored_by:
    print(
        f"Bucket {row['bucket']}: {row['count']} animes (Range: {int(row['min_scored_by'])}-{int(row['max_scored_by'])})"
    )

Prepare Data for ALS¶

We did clean ups but lets be sure we dont have null cells in rows. Otherwise ALS can fail.

In [344]:
# Filter out any null values in the cleaned_users_animes_df
ratings_df = cleaned_users_animes_df.filter(
    col("username").isNotNull() & 
    col("anime_id").isNotNull() & 
    col("my_score").isNotNull()
)
In [345]:
from pyspark.ml.feature import StringIndexer

# Convert username (string) to userId (numeric)
# ALS requires numeric IDs for both users and items
# Save the indexer model to use later for converting back to usernames
indexer = StringIndexer(inputCol="username", outputCol="userId", handleInvalid="skip")
username_indexer_model = indexer.fit(ratings_df)
ratings_df = username_indexer_model.transform(ratings_df)
In [346]:
ratings_df = ratings_df.select(
    col("username"),
    col("userId").cast("int"), 
    col("anime_id").cast("int").alias("itemId"), 
    col("my_score").cast("float").alias("rating")
)

import os
import shutil 

# Define the directory for saving the best model
MODEL_SAVE_DIR = "trained_models"
BEST_MODEL_PATH = os.path.join(MODEL_SAVE_DIR, "best_model")

if not os.path.exists(MODEL_SAVE_DIR):
    os.makedirs(MODEL_SAVE_DIR)
    print(f"Created directory: {MODEL_SAVE_DIR}")
else:
    print(f"Directory '{MODEL_SAVE_DIR}' already exists.")


def save_model(model):
    # before saving, check if the directory already exists and remove it
    if os.path.exists(BEST_MODEL_PATH):
        shutil.rmtree(BEST_MODEL_PATH) 
        print(f"Removed existing model at {BEST_MODEL_PATH}")

    # Save the best model so far
    try:
        model.write().save(BEST_MODEL_PATH)
        print(f"Model saved to {BEST_MODEL_PATH}")
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"Error saving model: {e}")

from pyspark.ml.evaluation import RegressionEvaluator
from pyspark.ml.recommendation import ALS
import time


# We'll try different combinations of based on requirements:
# - rank: number of latent (secret) factors (hidden features) in the model
# - iterations: how many times to optimize the model
# - lambda: regularization parameter to prevent overfitting

ranks = [10, 50, 200]
iterations = [10, 50, 200]
lambdas = [0.01, 0.1]


# will save the results of each model
results = []
best_model = None

# create a RegressionEvaluator to evaluate the model performance
evaluator_rmse = RegressionEvaluator(metricName="rmse", labelCol="rating", predictionCol="prediction")
evaluator_mse = RegressionEvaluator(metricName="mse", labelCol="rating", predictionCol="prediction")

print("Starting ALS hyperparameter tuning loop...")
print(f"Will train {len(ranks) * len(iterations) * len(lambdas)} models...")


# Loop through all parameter combinations (18 total models)
for rank in ranks:
    for num_iterations in iterations:
        for reg_param in lambdas:
            # Create the ALS model with current parameters
            # Parameters explained:
            # - maxIter: maximum iterations for optimization
            # - rank: number of latent factors (model complexity)
            # - regParam: regularization parameter (prevents overfitting)
            # - coldStartStrategy="drop": ignore users/items with no training data
            # - nonnegative=True: ensures predictions are non-negative
            als = ALS(
                maxIter=num_iterations,
                rank=rank,
                regParam=reg_param,
                userCol="userId",
                itemCol="itemId",
                ratingCol="rating",
                coldStartStrategy="drop",
                nonnegative=True,
            )

            print(f"Training model with: rank={rank}, iterations={num_iterations}, lambda={reg_param}")

            start_time = time.time()

            model = als.fit(train_data)

            end_time = time.time()
            training_time = end_time - start_time

            print(f"Model trained in {training_time:.2f} seconds")

            print("Making predictions on test data...")
            predictions = model.transform(test_data)
            print("Predictions made.")

            # Note: `coldStartStrategy="drop"` handles users/items in test set but not in training.
            # However, predictions can still be NaN if the model couldn't generate one for a valid pair.
            # RegressionEvaluator will error out on NaNs, so we must drop them.
            predictions_clean = predictions.na.drop(subset=["prediction"])

            # Evaluate the model
            rmse = evaluator_rmse.evaluate(predictions_clean)
            mse = evaluator_mse.evaluate(predictions_clean)

            print(f"RMSE = {rmse:.4f} (lower is better)")
            print(f"MSE = {mse:.4f} (lower is better)")

            # Check if this model is the best so far
            # if best_model is None then set it to the current model (for first iteration)
            if best_model is None:
                best_model = model
                save_model(best_model)
            else:
                # get the previous best RMSE from results
                prev_best_rmse = min([result["rmse"] for result in results]) if results else float("inf")
                # if current rmse is lower than the previous best RMSE, then this is the new best model
                if rmse < prev_best_rmse:
                    best_model = model
                    save_model(best_model)
                    print("Found a new best model!")

            # Store the results for this iteration
            results.append(
                {
                    "rank": rank,
                    "iterations": num_iterations,
                    "lambda": reg_param,
                    "rmse": rmse,
                    "mse": mse,
                    "training_time": training_time,
                }
            )

            print("-" * 50)

print("\nHyperparameter tuning finished.")

Model Performance Evaluation¶

We trained 18 ALS models with different combinations of rank (10, 50, 200), iterations (10, 50, 200), and lambda (0.01, 0.1). For each model, we calculated the Mean Squared Error (MSE) and Root Mean Squared Error (RMSE) on the test set.

Explanation of Metrics

  • MSE (Mean Squared Error): This is the average of the squares of the errors (the difference between actual and predicted ratings). Squaring the errors penalizes larger errors more heavily. A lower MSE indicates a better fit to the data.

  • RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error): This is the square root of the MSE. It brings the metric back to the original unit of the rating scale, making it more interpretable. For example, if your ratings are on a 1-10 scale, an RMSE of 1.5 means that, on average, the model's predictions are off by about 1.5 rating points. A lower RMSE indicates better model performance.

Why is this the best model?

The best model has the lowest RMSE and MSE among all tested configurations. Increasing both the rank and iterations allows the model to better capture the latent structure in the data, while a higher lambda (0.10) helps prevent overfitting.

RMSE Trends

  • Increasing iterations generally improves RMSE, especially for higher rank values.
  • Higher rank (more latent factors) also tends to improve RMSE, but with diminishing returns and increased computation time.
  • Lambda: A value of 0.10 consistently outperforms 0.01, indicating that stronger regularization is beneficial for this dataset.

X-axis: Prediction Error (Actual - Predicted)

This represents the difference between the actual ratings users gave to animes and what our best model predicted Negative values mean the model over-predicted (predicted higher than actual) Positive values mean the model under-predicted (predicted lower than actual) Zero would be a perfect prediction

Y-axis: Count

Shows how many predictions fall into each error range The height of each bar indicates the frequency of that particular error magnitude

Key observations from the chart

  • Distribution Shape: The histogram shows a normal (bell-curve) distribution centered very close to zero, which is excellent news for our model's performance.
  • Mean Error: 0.213 (shown in green line)

This means our model has a very slight tendency to under-predict ratings by about 0.2 points on average This is remarkably close to zero, indicating minimal systematic bias

  • Standard Deviation: 1.337

Shows the spread of errors around the mean Most predictions fall within about ±2.67 rating points (2 standard deviations)

  • Concentration Around Zero: The majority of predictions cluster around the red dashed line (perfect prediction), indicating our model is quite accurate for most cases.

In other words:

The tight distribution around zero shows our ALS model with parameters (rank=200, iterations=200, lambda=0.10) is performing very well. The small mean error (0.213) indicates no significant systematic bias. Most errors fall within a reasonable range for a 5-10 rating scale.

import numpy as np
from pyspark.sql.functions import udf
from pyspark.sql.types import FloatType

def cosineSimilarity(target_features, incoming_features):
    dot = np.dot(target_features, incoming_features)
    norma = np.linalg.norm(target_features)
    normb = np.linalg.norm(incoming_features)
    cos = dot / (norma * normb + 1e-6)
    return float(cos)

# Create user defined function (UDF) for cosine similarity
# What is UDF?
# A UDF allows us to define a custom function that can be applied to DataFrame columns
cosine_udf = udf(lambda features: cosineSimilarity(target_anime_features, features), FloatType())
In [ ]:
# Calculate similarity for all animes except the target
manual_similarities = (
    item_factors.filter(col("id") != target_anime_id)
    .withColumn("similarity", cosine_udf(col("features")))
    .select("id", "similarity")
    .orderBy(col("similarity").desc())
    .limit(25)
)

# Join with anime titles for better readability
manual_top25 = manual_similarities.join(
    cleaned_animes_df.select("anime_id", "title", "score"), manual_similarities.id == cleaned_animes_df.anime_id, "left"
).select("anime_id", "title", "score", "similarity")

print("Top 25 most similar animes to Fullmetal Alchemist: Brotherhood (Manual Calculation):")

from pyspark.sql.types import FloatType

# Get all user factors from the ALS model
user_factors = loaded_best_model.userFactors


def predict_rating(user_features):
    return float(np.dot(user_features, target_anime_features))


# Create a UDF to calculate the predicted rating based on dot product
predict_rating_udf = udf(predict_rating, FloatType())

# Calculate predicted ratings for all users
top10_will_like_target_anime_manual = (
    user_factors.withColumn("predicted_rating", predict_rating_udf(col("features")))
    .select("id", "predicted_rating")
    .orderBy(col("predicted_rating").desc())
    .limit(10)
)
